Prologue
I stood barefoot in the sand, watching the sun bleed into the Pacific. The waves
rolled in slow and heavy, like a great machine that had forgotten its purpose but
kept moving anyway.
It was April 2025.
I was fifty-seven years old.
And for the first time in twenty five years, I was alone, in a new place, nothing
familiar, no one I knew to call, have a drink or share a cozy intimate meal with.
Behind me stretched the years:
I thought about connections that shaped me. My first loves, and the heat of those
early experiences. Those first connections between machines were foundational
too. The first time I connected my computer to another one over a telephone line.
The first time I sent an email a decade before the internet. These were early
portals into the future. Both my own future, and the future of the world. Machine
and man, weaving around each other like the strands of the double-helix.
These early experiences were like magic. A dream of what could come, what
would come.
In those early years, I believed that love — like technology — would inevitably
evolve, improve, endure. We would grow together, deepening, strengthening,
improving. It would be the virtuous cycle, man and woman, machine and man,
each reinforcing the other to strive towards a better future.
A career spent walking side by side with the machine. Working with it, shaping
it and it shaping me. Believing in the machine – that within it lay an answer.
Not THE answer but an answer that would serve both myself and the word.
A marriage built on care and hope, weathered by silence and stagnation.
Friendships lost, companies fallen, dreams eroded grain by grain.

I couldn't understand it then:
connection isn’t the same as intimacy.
Progress isn’t the same as belonging.
The world raced forward.
And somewhere along the way, we drifted apart.
And here is stand, looking out at the majesty of creation and wonder where it all
went so wrong.
The Mayflower
I was a passenger on the Mayflower of the digital age.
No, really.
Today we talk about “digital natives” — people born in the 1980s or later who
grew up with computers and the internet woven into their lives.
But I was one of the first to ever land on these shores.
One of the few who helped cut down the trees, build the first camps, start the first
communities.
A key difference with the old metaphor:
In this New World, there were no indigenous people.
No one to displace. No ancient cities to conquer.
We stepped into a vast, empty space and tried to build the future we dreamed of.
A dream given form.
A dream where we would use technology to build ourselves up —
to forge new connections, to make each other better.
We were a tribe. A tribe of pioneers, of true believers, of idealists.
And when the rest of the world finally came rushing in, all our human frailties
came with them.

Pride.
Greed.
Lust.
Envy.
Gluttony.
Wrath.
Sloth.
All of it.
Because we are human.
Because we can’t help ourselves.
Because we never learn.
This is the story of how that dream — the dream of the machine — came to life.
It’s also the story of my own dreams.
The dreams of the person I hoped, and believed, I might become.
Neither dream ended up as expected.
But neither dream’s ending is written yet.
This is that story.
