Nezek
The dream is still there, lodged like a splinter in my mind.
It’s hard to say how old I was at the time — I think a young teenager.
In the dream, I’m walking through an industrial city: brutal architecture, cold.
The sky and the buildings are all gray.
There’s a feeling of heaviness, of oppression, all around.
I wander through the gray streets and there’s no one around.
I’m looking for someone — anyone — to talk to.
What is this place? Why am I all alone here?
I begin to hear a faint sound — a mechanical thrum.
Pulsing, almost breathing.
The tension is palpable as I continue navigating the lifeless streets, trying to find
the source of the sound, trying to find anything. Anyone.

As I turn a corner, I see a large industrial building — maybe a factory — looming
before me.
Jutting from the top of the building, almost like scars rending the sky, were three
smokestacks billowing dark ash.
Upon each smokestack was a letter. A Hebrew letter.
On the leftmost: נ (nun).
On the middle: ז (zayin).
On the last: ק (kaf).
What did it mean?
I didn’t know the word.
Suddenly awake in my bed, the dream lingered,
like black ash hanging in the air from those smokestacks.
I was sweating, anxious, but uncertain.
I knew this was important — meant something — but what?
The dream reminded me of Camazotz, from A Wrinkle in Time —
that place of tyranny, cruelty, suffering.
The dream wouldn’t let go.
I tried to get some more rest but slept fitfully through the rest of the night.
A few days later, at Hebrew afternoon school,
I had a chance to speak with Rabbi Zweig.
“Rabbi, do the letters נ-ז-ק spell anything in Hebrew?”
He arched an eyebrow beneath his glasses and said,
“Yes. The word is ‘nezek’ — נ-ז-ק. It means ‘damage’ or ‘harm’. Why?”
My chest tightened. “So… kind of like destruction?” I asked.
“No, not exactly. In Halacha — Jewish Law — it often refers to physical harm
someone causes to another person or their property.
If something is hurt, or diminished in value somehow, that is nezek.
So, Mayer Dov — it’s an interesting question. Why are you asking?”
“Oh, it’s nothing. I think I just saw it in a book somewhere,” I said, walking away.

As those smokestacks scarred the sky in my dream,
I carried the scar of that dream along with me throughout my life.
Nezek.
Harm.
Damage.
My mother’s haunted eyes, sitting on the edge of the bathtub,
unable to tell me she loved me.
My father’s rage — at his own father —
for never being able to love him,
for never feeling good enough, worthy enough.
My sister, always pushing, always demanding attention,
it never being enough.
My own self.
Always needing love, reassurance, care.
Making myself small.
To not be the problem.
To make it right.
To fix it.
Damage.
Harm.
Even as a very young person, my soul knew what I was up against.
Nezek.
The damage and harm done to my parents and their parents before them.
The damage and harm done to the Jewish people over centuries and millennia.
Nezek was genetic.
Nezek was cultural.
Nezek was imprinted on me from before I was born.
Nezek was The Pattern.

