Ben Affleck character in Chasing Amy. It was doomed from the start, and I was
there was no way I wasn't going to get hurt in the process. Somewhere I knew
that, but I kept going, and I don't have to tell you again why. The golem was
taking shape.
I arrived at the restaurant a few minutes early and she was already there. We
were shown to a pre-seating area and offered a drink before being shown to our
table. Over drinks we chatted more, and the conversation was so easy. She
spoke to the wait staff in Spanish and I was smitten. After a short time, we were
show to our table. A round table where we sat a 90° from one another. Close
enough for me to reach out and touch her but I dared not. Each course was
brought out and we savored each bite and I savored every moment of the dinner
with her.
I wanted to wrap my arms around her, pull her close, hold her, merge with her. I
reached out my hand to her across the table and she took it. Electricity shot up
my arm at her touch.

Early Interactions with The Machine
I was drawn to the machine as early as I can remember. As a child of the 70's my
generation was the first to have 'electronic toys'. The Mattel Electronic Football
and Baseball, Merlin, Blip Digital Derby, Talking Viewmaster and of course –
Pong. The list goes on. These were amazing toys pushing the boundaries of what
was technically possbible in the late 1970s.
At that time the personal computers was just becoming a thing. While I was
playing PONG with Mark D at his house, Steve Woznia and Steve Jobs were
inventing the future in a garage in Cupertino. In many ways, those two young men
were building my future too.
In London Ontario in the late 70's my family didn't have a computer, yet, but I had
my ways of getting my hands on these magical devices. I remember taking the
bus with my friend Joseph Knondakar to a computer shop about 5km away from
where we lived. You could rent time on one of their Commodore PET computers.
You know the one. All in one machine with a tiny green screen slapped on top.
This was like an internet cafe, before there was the internet. And there was no
coffee either. I don't remember what we actually did on this machine, but I
remember being transfixed.
Soon after my school got the same machine in our library and Joseph and I would
spend more time in there playing some kind of 'educational' game. I don't know
what crazy person at my school arranged to have a computer in our library
around 1980, before anyone knew what they were actually for or good at, but I
thank that person. Truly.
I craved interaction with The Machine. I pined for it. My friend Zvi and I would lust
over the Radio Shack catalog looking at the TRS-80s. We agreed that we would
save our allowance, and buy one together. I told my mom, and she told me I was
crazy. How exactly are you going to share custody of a computer at 12 years old.
I waited.
After my bar-mitzvah I finally got my first "real" computer. An Atari 400. It had a
rdiculous membrane keyboard that was impossible to type on, a cartridge slot to
play games, and a cassette drive to store and load programs. If you've never
used a cassette drive before, and you almost certainly haven't, it was a special

kind of hell. The program was literally stored on tape as a series of shieks,
squawks and whirs, and the computer would listen to the analog 'song' being
played and load it into memory. The rub though, was that cassette tapes are
famously finicky. Dust, the tape stretching slightly, your sister jumping around, or
a butterfly flapping its wings in China could cause the entire load to flail. You'd
wait for 15 minutes for the computer to 'listen' and load this game you were dying
to play, and when it reached 98% completed. ERROR. It was maddening.
But this was a 'real' computer. You could put the BASIC cartridge in and create
real programs.
10 PRINT "MARK IS COOL"
20 GOTO 10
Joy. I could make the machine do anything I wanted.
But mostly I played games. Incredible wonderful games created by visionary
artists who created magic within unbelievable constraints.
Me and The Machine. It was love at first sight.
Caverns of Mars - an incredible vertical scrolling shooter
Venture - a very early precuror to Diablo and a whole genre of dungeon
crawlers
Star Raiders - every first person shooter ever
Jawbreaker - the best pac mac clone
Eastern Front - an incredible strategy game with mind blowing AI for it's time
about the German eastern front during WWII.
Calvados and Kind of Blue
In the dream I'm walking through a beautiful old manor house. I hear the soft
sounds of jazz trumpet echoing through the halls. I follow the sound, trying to find
the source of it. I walk down a long hall as the music gets louder. The sound is
coming from the room just ahead. Crossing the threshold of the study it's all warm
wood and brown leather. The scent of old books and smoky spirits linger in the
air. The walls are covered in bookshelves. So many books. There's a turntable in

the corner, record spinning, the soft sound of All Blues from Miles Davis Kind of
Blue filling the room.
She is there, sitting in a leather armchair, one leg tucked under the other, wearing
a deep plum velvet smoking jacket that looks like it's been tailored just for her.
She looks up from the book in her hand and she reaches for a bottle in front of
her and pours a dark amber liquid into two small glasses that sit on the table in
front of her. She doesn't ask. She already knows. I walk towards her and sit in the
chair beside her. She hands me the glass. Calvados. Domain Dupont Hors d’Age.
I sink into the soft leather chair and see that she's reading Rilke.
I take a sip from the glass. That apple warmth, that slow amber fire—it’s like
memory in a glass. Autumn afternoons and apples. The childhood memory of fruit
filtered through a long life lived.
She looks at me and starts to read from the book
"Tell me," she whispers. "How does that make you feel?"
And I do. Oh I do.
"I am much too alone in this world, yet not alone enough to truly
consecrate the hour."
"Love your solitude and try to sing out with the pain it causes
you."